[2
Date: 23 Nov 2001 (pre-release version available on-line 21 Nov 2001)
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: MMWR Morb Mortal Wkly Rep 2001; 50(46): 1035-6. [edited
<http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5046a3.htm>

Unexplained deaths following knee surgery -- Minnesota, Nov 2001
-----------------------------------------
The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) are assisting The
Minnesota Department of Health (MDOH) in the investigation of the deaths of
3 previously healthy people who died unexpectedly following uncomplicated
knee surgery.
All 3 patients became ill between one and 4 days after surgery. Symptoms
included severe abdominal pain and a sudden decline in blood pressure
followed by a fulminant course with death within 24 hours of symptom onset.
The clinical course was consistent with septic or cardiogenic shock. After
5 days of incubation, a blood culture taken from one of the patients
yielded _Clostridium sordellii_. The source of infection in the one patient
and the cause of death in all patients remain unknown.
In response to these deaths, MDOH is recommending that all elective knee
surgery in Minnesota be suspended pending findings of the investigation. To
identify possible cases in other areas, CDC is seeking reports of patients
who have had orthopedic surgery since 1 Oct 2001, involving the knee or
other large joint, and within 7 days following surgery who have had
hypotension and other clinical findings of cardiogenic or septic shock or
abdominal pain of no other identified cause and who have required intensive
care or have died. Clinicians should report such patients to their state
health department or CDC's Division of Healthcare Quality Promotion,
telephone 800-893-0485.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[_Clostridium sordellii_is an anaerobic Gram positive spore-forming
bacillus found in soil. It rarely causes human disease. A review of the
literature has revealed mostly case reports and the occasional small
"series" of case reports. Clinical presentations have included abscess with
sepsis, septic arthritis, and postpartum fatal toxic shock syndrome.
Identification of clostridium sepsis in one of the patients is intriguing
as a possible outcome of a contamination of common product/instrument used
in knee surgery or other orthopedic surgical procedures. As stated in the
MMWR article, the isolation of _C. sordellii_ from one patient so far just
confirms the probable cause of death of that one patient. Publishing a
national alert in the MMWR increases the likelihood of uncovering
additional cases if there is a problem with _C. sordellii_ contamination of
products/instruments used for orthopedic surgical procedures. Further
information is awaited. - Mod.MPP
Some selected references of interest are included below.
1: Rorbye C, Petersen IS, Nilas L. Postpartum Clostridium sordellii
infection associated with fatal toxic shock syndrome. Acta Obstet Gynecol
Scand 2000; 79(12): 1134-5.
2: Abdulla A, Yee L. The clinical spectrum of Clostridium sordellii
bacteraemia: two case reports and a review of the literature. J Clin Pathol
2000; 53(9): 709-12.
3: Gredlein CM, Silverman ML, Downey MS. Polymicrobial septic arthritis due
to Clostridium species: case report and review. Clin Infect Dis 2000;
30(3): 590-4.
4: Borer A, Gilad J, Sikuler E, Riesenberg K, Schlaeffer F, Buskila D.
Fatal Clostridium sordellii ischio-rectal abscess with septicaemia
complicating ultrasound-guided transrectal prostate biopsy. J Infect 1999;
38(2): 128-9.
5: Lewis CJ, Naylor RD. Sudden death in sheep associated with Clostridium
sordellii. Vet Rec 1998; 142(16): 417-21.
6: Hungerland E, Eiring P, Bultmann B. [Clostridium sordellii sepsis with
intravascular haemolysis. Dtsch Med Wochenschr 1997;122(42): 1281-4.
7: Spera RV Jr, Kaplan MH, Allen SL. Clostridium sordellii bacteremia: case
report and review. Clin Infect Dis 1992; 15(6): 950-4.
